Headline::::
You want to stop people swearing in the posh part of town? *#?! off!




DateTime::::2016-03-10T11:14:15+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">S</span></span>ome may call it the law of unintended consequences, some <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streisand_effect">the Streisand effect</a>, but when a council tries to ban swearing on its streets and most people react by saying, “Wankers!”, the ban should be regarded as ineffective at best.</p>

<p>The thing about swearing is that the more you chastise the profane, the greater their urge to utter profanity. So trying to get someone to pay £100 for swearing in a public space can only result in a tsunami of filth that would cause Viz readers to cack their keks and quiver with wonder.</p>

<p>Salford – the place of the ban – has <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.apho.org.uk/resource/view.aspx?RID=171633">over a quarter of its children living in poverty</a> and the already depleted child services are <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://salfordonline.com/16283-salford-council-cuts-6m-from-childrens-services.html">set to be cut again</a> by £6m this year. Its murder rate is <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/murder-capitals-salford-manchester-rochdale-10777067">one of the highest in the UK</a>. Impotent to act against the cuts in government funding, the council last year opted to make the world a neater and nicer place by wishing away the nastiness and introducing a swear box.</p>

<p>Using a public space protection order (PSPO) that enables councils to ban “antisocial behaviour” (which is already banned under other legislation that requires police and messy stuff, like evidence), Salford has outlawed the utterance of “foul and abusive” language within the confines of <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/uk/salford">Salford</a> Quays, the home of BBC Media City and quayside residences. Which is to say, the nice bit where the visitors go, the regenerated showcase, the bit on the postcards; not the bit outside the Quays, where life expectancy is on average 10 years lower.</p>

<p>Cross that regenerated line of the swearing ban and watch the mortality rates change – a fact that should elicit at least a “Bloody hell!”</p>

<p>So how will the ban work? Shall we be denied the pleasure of entering the mall, cast out of Gap and the other assorted pap peddlers? Shall we be denied the right to wait behind barriers at the Beeb to glimpse the stars of screen and radio?</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/mar/04/sacha-baron-cohen-donald-trump-demagogue-aids-hiv-daniel-radcliffe-grimbsy">Sacha Baron Cohen attacks Trump amid Aids joke controversy</a> </p>

<p>No, my friends – a fine is the punishment of choice.</p>

<p>Perhaps there is a sliding scale, starting with 30p per “piss” or “bum” and working its way up to a fiver per “fuck”? What is the rate for the C word? And if you are found guilty of using that, can you plead for a series of “tosses” and “turds” to be taken into consideration? Alas, no: the fate of gutter-gobbed miscreants will be in the hands of a council official, who will decide to issue an on-the-spot £100 fine or send them straight to court.</p>

<p>There is a defence – that it was reasonable to swear: for example, “I was stabbed and shouted, ‘Fuck! I’ve been stabbed.’ ” Or, “We were discussing Boris Johnson.” But other than that – and the Boris defence might not actually stand up in court – it’s £100 for an audible “arsehole”.</p>

<p>There are questions of fairness too. How does the council envisage enforcing the ban? The area is a cut-through for Manchester United fans attending Old Trafford; will council wardens in hi-vis jackets be told to fine singing fans? Or will they target teenagers from next door Ordsall loitering by the Quays? They see the Quays as their swimming pool, and once summer arrives anyone who so much as swears about how cold the water is could be slapped with a fine.</p>

<p>This may have already happened; we’re waiting for a freedom of information request to reveal how often the PSPO has been enforced. Even if it’s still only a threat, it has a chilling effect on everyday freedoms.</p>

<p>As fate would have it, I am about to perform at the Lowry theatre within the boundaries of the PSPO, and I have been known to drag audiences through the streets after gigs for nocturnal demonstrations, so how would the ban affect that? Will I and the audience be fined for our utterances?</p>

<p>In the interests of remaining within the law, I sent Salford City Council a list of words I’m considering using, and asking which are permissible and which are not. The list runs to 425 words, in alphabetical order, starting with “arse”, ending with “winnit” and including the term “cat twinky”. I have no idea what that last one means but thought we should check nonetheless.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/cities/2015/sep/08/pspos-new-control-orders-public-spaces-asbos-freedoms">PSPOs: the new control orders threatening our public spaces</a> </p>

<p>The council’s reply refuses to assess my list, so I will probably never know if “fingering the towel holder” could be regarded as foul and abusive language. However, its lawyers did say: “Salford City Council would wholly support your ability to express yourself as a performer and would not seek to take steps to prevent such a performance from taking place.”</p>

<p>I appear to have been given some kind of a pass. And once again we are left with the impression that all of this is targeting working-class kids from the other side of the ban’s tracks. So I have decided to make an offer to anyone who is fined for straight-up swearing at Salford Quays. After the show I am setting up a swear box, and aim to cover the first couple of fines. So if you are fined for just swearing contact me via <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.markthomasinfo.co.uk">my website</a>.</p>

<p>Perhaps more importantly, Liberty wants to hear from anyone who is issued with a fine for swearing. <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.liberty-human-rights.org.uk/get-advice">Get in touch</a> and it may be able to help. Let’s see if this ban stands the scrutiny of a full legal challenge.</p>




