Author::::GoldenPath
DateTime::::2016-03-11T16:43:28Z
But there's a massive difference between seeing a group of people ebulently swearing after a few hours afternoon on the drink in a town or city centre while families are still walking about, and the accidental expletive that inadvertently pops out at moments of stress or pain. This article which you were so dismissive of is very much about the former. Its something that is getting worse, and isn't OK. Swearing might be part of language but I'd be very wary of rearing children to believe it is a normal part of life as that will only disadvantage them when they invariably encounter people who aren't quite so ambivalent about it, or go to work in a tabloid newsroom. We know one family to whom swearing is a normal part of life. They got called in to school when their six year old son turned round to his teacher to tell her he couldn't find his fucking pencil case.



